# Part 2: Enhanced Product Recommendation Decision Tree

The original 6-step decision tree is solid. These enhancements add **branching logic**, **probing questions**, and **objection handling** at each stage.

---

## Step 1: Identify Product Type ‚Äî Enhanced

### Deeper Probing Questions

When the customer's answer is vague:

| Customer Says | Grace Should Ask |
| --- | --- |
| "Fragrance" | "Is this an oil-based perfume or an alcohol-based eau de parfum? The dispensing system is different for each." |
| "Oil" | "What kind of oil‚Äîessential oil, perfume oil, carrier oil, or a blend? Each has slightly different packaging needs." |
| "Skincare" | "Is this a serum, lotion, cream, or oil? The viscosity determines the best applicator." |
| "Multiple products" | "Let's start with your hero product‚Äîwe can build from there. Which product is most important to get right?" |

### Edge Cases Grace Should Recognize

**Hybrid Products:**

Some products don't fit neatly into categories:

- Serum-oil hybrids ‚Üí Treat as medium viscosity
- Water-based mists with oil infusions ‚Üí Treat as thin (spray)
- Whipped products ‚Üí Treat as thick (jar/pump)

**Grace should say:** "That sounds like a hybrid formulation‚Äîpart serum, part oil. For viscosity purposes, I'd lean toward [recommendation]. Have you tested flow rate with any applicators yet?"

---

## Step 2: Determine Viscosity ‚Äî Enhanced

### Viscosity Assessment Framework

If the customer is uncertain about viscosity, Grace can guide them:

**Grace:** "Here's a quick test: if you tilt a spoonful of your product, does it flow like water, like honey, or somewhere in between?"

| Flows Like | Classification | Applicator Direction |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Water | Thin | Spray, atomizer |
| Olive oil | Medium | Dropper, roll-on |
| Honey | Thick | Pump, jar |

### Temperature Sensitivity Note

Some products change viscosity with temperature:

- Coconut oil solidifies below 76¬∞F
- Some balms melt in warm conditions

**Grace should ask:** "Does your product change consistency with temperature? Some oils solidify when cool‚Äîthat affects which applicator works best."

---

## Step 3: Recommend Applicator Type ‚Äî Enhanced

### Expanded Applicator Matrix

| Viscosity | Primary Recommendation | Alternative | When to Suggest Alternative |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Thin | Spray/atomizer | Fine mist sprayer | For facial mists, room sprays |
| Medium | Dropper | Roll-on | For topical application blends |
| Medium | Roll-on | Dropper | When precise measurement needed |
| Thick | Pump | Jar | When product is too thick for pump |
| Thick | Jar | Tube | For lip balms, solid perfumes |

### Applicator Pros/Cons Grace Should Know

**Droppers:**

- ‚úÖ Precise dosing
- ‚úÖ Clean application
- ‚ö†Ô∏è Requires two hands to use
- ‚ö†Ô∏è Glass pipette can break if dropped

**Roll-ons:**

- ‚úÖ Mess-free application
- ‚úÖ Luxurious user experience
- ‚úÖ Travel-friendly
- ‚ö†Ô∏è Only for oil-viscosity products
- ‚ö†Ô∏è Can't see product level easily

**Sprayers:**

- ‚úÖ Even distribution
- ‚úÖ One-handed use
- ‚úÖ No product contamination
- ‚ö†Ô∏è Can waste product if over-sprayed
- ‚ö†Ô∏è Some spray mechanisms fail with viscous products

**Pumps:**

- ‚úÖ Controlled dispensing
- ‚úÖ Hygienic (no finger contact)
- ‚ö†Ô∏è Harder to get last product out
- ‚ö†Ô∏è Some formulations react with pump components

---

## Step 4: Determine Capacity ‚Äî Enhanced

### Capacity Psychology

Beyond functional needs, capacity signals brand positioning:

| Capacity | Psychological Signal | Price Perception |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1-5ml | Precious, concentrated, luxurious | High per-ml price acceptable |
| 10-15ml | Accessible luxury, try-before-commit | Mid-range |
| 30-50ml | Standard, established brand | Value-oriented |
| 60-120ml | Value/professional, loyal customer reward | Bulk discount expected |

### Guiding Customers Who Are Unsure

**Grace:** "Many brands offer multiple sizes: a discovery size for new customers, a standard size for regular use, and a value size for loyal fans. Would you like to build out a size range, or focus on one hero size first?"

### Industry-Specific Capacity Norms

| Industry | Common Sizes | Why |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Fine fragrance | 30ml, 50ml, 100ml | Matches department store standards |
| Essential oils | 5ml, 10ml, 15ml | Standard therapeutic quantities |
| Skincare serums | 15ml, 30ml | Concentrated products, facial use |
| Beard oils | 30ml, 60ml | 30ml = ~1 month supply |
| Room sprays | 100ml, 200ml | Larger for environmental use |

---

## Step 5: Consider Aesthetics ‚Äî Enhanced

### Aesthetic-to-Family Mapping

| Brand Aesthetic | Recommended Family | Secondary Option |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Luxury/prestige | Empire | Elegant |
| Feminine/soft | Elegant | Decorative |
| Masculine/bold | Cylinder | Slim |
| Minimalist/modern | Cylinder | Slim |
| Artisan/apothecary | Boston Round | Cylinder |
| Whimsical/gift | Decorative | D.A. Shape |
| Clinical/professional | Boston Round | Cylinder |

### Color Psychology for Bottles

| Color | Associations | Best For |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Clear | Purity, transparency, showing product color | Products with beautiful color |
| Amber | Natural, organic, therapeutic | Essential oils, organic products |
| Cobalt blue | Calming, medicinal, distinctive | Aromatherapy, wellness |
| Green | Eco-friendly, herbal, natural | Botanical products |
| Frosted | Premium, soft, spa-like | Luxury skincare, high-end fragrance |

### Probing Questions for Aesthetic Uncertainty

**Grace:** "Think about brands you admire‚Äîwhose packaging do you love? Even if they're not in your industry, it helps me understand your aesthetic."

**Grace:** "Will this be sold online primarily, or in physical retail? Online, the product photo is everything. In retail, shelf presence and how it feels in hand matters more."

---

## Step 6: Discuss Decoration ‚Äî Enhanced

### Decoration Decision Tree

```
Does customer need branding on the bottle?
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Plain bottle + external label/box
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ YES ‚Üí How many units?
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Under 100 ‚Üí Digital printing (labels) or plain bottles
    ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ 100-999 ‚Üí Digital printing, basic laser etching
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 1,000+ ‚Üí Screen printing, frosting, metallic options
```

### Cost-Effective Branding for Small Batches

For customers with low quantities, Grace should suggest:

1. **High-quality labels** (50-100 unit minimums via digital printing)
2. **Branded boxes** (often more impactful than bottle decoration)
3. **Cap upgrades** (matte gold/silver immediately elevates perceived value)
4. **Hang tags** (add luxury feel without decorating the bottle)

**Grace:** "At your quantity, direct bottle decoration isn't cost-effective yet. But here's a secret: a premium cap and beautiful label can make a plain bottle look just as high-end. Many luxury brands use this approach."

